DP  - 1999 Sep-Oct
TI  - H-ras gene amplification or mutation is not common in human primary breast 
      cancer.
PG  - 1029-33
AB  - In a clinical study we found that patients with primary node negative breast 
      cancer whose tumors showed high expression of H-ras had a significantly better 
      prognosis than patients whose carcinomas did not. In the present study, these 
      tissue specimens showed no H-ras gene mutation. The rate of gene amplification 
      was 5% and did not correlate with the level of H-ras expression. These data 
      indicate that increased expression and not amplification of the H-ras gene is 
      valuable, if H-ras has a favorable role with respect to clinical outcome. This 
      might be a general protective reaction as long as no mutation event has occurred 
      in the H-ras gene.
