DP  - 1999 Nov
TI  - Recent advances in breast cancer biology.
PG  - 429-34
AB  - Breast cancer remains the leading cause of death in American women 30 to 70 years 
      of age, and research in the field of breast cancer continues at an explosive 
      pace. Our understanding of the molecular basis of familial breast cancer has 
      advanced significantly through investigation of the tumor suppressor gene BRCA1, 
      as has our knowledge of the role of the ATM gene and predisposition to breast 
      cancer in ataxia-telangiectasia carriers. In addition, progress has been made in 
      understanding the role of HER-2/neu as a prognostic factor in breast cancer. In 
      this review, some of the recent advances in breast cancer biology that are 
      relevant to these areas of study are highlighted.
