VI  - 121
IP  - 8
DP  - 1999
TI  - [Clinical importance of histology, grading and ploidies in primary breast 
      cancer].
PG  - 384-8
AB  - OBJECTIVE: In order to characterise carcinoma of the breast the determination of 
      ploidy can be used in addition to established prognostic factors such as 
      histology and grading. The aim of the investigation was to establish the 
      association between histology, grading and ploidy and to indicate the prognostic 
      and predictive value of these parameters in relation to disease free survival 
      (DFS) and overall survival (OS). MATERIAL AND METHODS: 125 consecutive cases of 
      primary breast carcinoma occurring between the years 1992-1995 were surveyed. The 
      median follow up time lasted 45 months. Correlation analyses were carried out 
      using the Chi-square test, Kaplan-Meier (univariate) and Cox (multivariate) 
      methods. RESULTS: Histology and grading showed no correlation to ploidy but seems 
      to be of importance for DFS in node-negative breast carcinoma. Ploidy did not 
      influence neither DFS nor OS. Ductal histology appeared to be a useful factor in 
      predicting the response of cases treated with an anti-oestrogen (Tamoxifen) since 
      in this group a higher relapse rate of 25% occurred. CONCLUSIONS: Ploidy appears 
      not to be of clinical importance.
