DP  - 1999 Mar
TI  - Ductal carcinoma in situ in breast carcinogenesis.
PG  - 383-4
AB  - Evidence is mounting that ductal carcinoma in situ (DCIS) is a direct precursor 
      of invasive breast cancer. Recent molecular biological and cytogenetic studies 
      have revealed chromosomal gains and losses involved in breast carcinogenesis. 
      This editorial discusses how the gains and losses on the different chromosomes 
      fit into previously defined morphological routes of progression from normal cells 
      through DCIS to invasive carcinoma, and the possible uses of these gains and 
      losses in the classification of DCIS and the risk assessment of DCIS patients.
