VI  - 32
IP  - 2-3
DP  - 1999 Apr-Jun
TI  - Association of pS2 (TFF1) release with breast tumour proliferative rate: in vitro 
      and in vivo studies.
PG  - 107-18
AB  - Although cytosolic expression of the protein pS2 (TFF1) is considered to be a 
      marker of oestrogen receptor (OR) function, there exists some clinical data to 
      suggest an inverse relationship of cytosolic pS2 to tumour proliferation. 
      Although secreted from breast cancer cells, the relationship of pS2 secretion to 
      tumour natural history has been little studied. The mechanisms and kinetics of 
      pS2 release and its relation to tumour cell proliferation were studied in a human 
      breast cancer cell line MCF-7 and verified in a preliminary clinical study. 
      Stimulation by stripped serum or oestradiol resulted in parallel increases of 
      proliferation and pS2 release in both time course and dose-response experiments. 
      Direct pharmacological alterations of proliferation were followed by identical 
      changes in pS2 release. The relationship between serum pS2 levels and tumour 
      proliferative activity when analysed as a function of steroid status showed a 
      slope of 0.56 in OR+ vs. 0.19 in OR- tumours. It is concluded that pS2 release 
      from breast cancer cells is associated with their proliferation and measurement 
      of serum pS2 levels might be a good predictor of tumour proliferative state and 
      could permit noninvasive monitoring of this tumour parameter.
