TI  - Perceptions of Herceptin: a monoclonal antibody for the treatment of breast 
      cancer.
PG  - 5-10
AB  - In September 1998 Trastuzumab (Herceptin) became the second monoclonal antibody 
      approved for the treatment of a malignant condition, and the first antibody 
      approved for the treatment of a solid tumor. It is a mouse-human chimeric 
      antibody that produces anti-tumor effects by blocking the HER2-neu receptor, and 
      can also interact with human immune cells to effect antibody dependent 
      cell-mediated cytotoxicity. Pivotal trials in breast cancer showed that it has 
      activity as a single agent in a subset of patients whose tumors greatly 
      over-express HER2, but results were even more impressive when it was used in 
      combination with chemotherapy. It should also prove to be useful in the treatment 
      of subsets of patients with other adenocarcinomas whose tumors over-express HER2.
