DP  - 1999 Sep
TI  - Breast Cancer Litigation: An Update with Practice Guidelines.
PG  - 335-339
AB  - Cases involving breast cancer are the second most common cause of malpractice 
      litigation. The leading allegation is failure to diagnose, followed by improper 
      treatment. The most common physicians involved are those giving direct care to 
      women: obstetricians/gynecologists, family medicine physicians, and internists. 
      This review addresses frequent areas of litigation, offering practice guidelines 
      for avoidance of malpractice claims. In addition, two new areas of breast cancer 
      management will be reviewed-breast cancer prevention and breast cancer genetic 
      testing-as potential new areas of malpractice litigation.
