TI  - Expression of wild-type estrogen receptor beta and variant isoforms in human 
      breast cancer.
PG  - 5425-8
AB  - It has been shown in previous studies that a variety of estrogen receptor (ER) 
      beta mRNA transcripts are expressed in human breast cancer cell lines and tumors. 
      To complement the RNA expression studies, we have developed ER-beta-specific 
      antibodies to characterize ER-beta protein expression in breast cancer cell lines 
      and tumors. Monoclonal antibodies were made against a peptide representing the 
      first 18 amino acids of the longest ER-beta open reading frame reported to date, 
      and polyclonal antibodies were made against a peptide within the ER-beta B 
      domain. By Western blot analysis, we show that ER-beta protein is expressed in 
      all cancer cell lines tested and in three of five breast tumor samples. The 
      breast cancer cell lines showed variation in the size of the expressed ER-beta 
      protein. The longest form detected was consistent with the 530-amino acid, 
      full-length ER-beta sequence. Shorter ER-beta isoforms were detected in the 
      ER-alpha-negative MDA-MB-231 and MDA-MB-435 breast cancer cell lines, likely 
      corresponding to previously described COOH-terminal RNA variant isoforms.
