DP  - 1999 Jul 30
TI  - Association of BRCA1 with the hRad50-hMre11-p95 complex and the DNA damage 
      response.
PG  - 747-50
AB  - BRCA1 encodes a tumor suppressor that is mutated in familial breast and ovarian 
      cancers. Here, it is shown that BRCA1 interacts in vitro and in vivo with hRad50, 
      which forms a complex with hMre11 and p95/nibrin. Upon irradiation, BRCA1 was 
      detected in discrete foci in the nucleus, which colocalize with hRad50. Formation 
      of irradiation-induced foci positive for BRCA1, hRad50, hMre11, or p95 was 
      dramatically reduced in HCC/1937 breast cancer cells carrying a homozygous 
      mutation in BRCA1 but was restored by transfection of wild-type BRCA1. Ectopic 
      expression of wild-type, but not mutated, BRCA1 in these cells rendered them less 
      sensitive to the DNA damage agent, methyl methanesulfonate. These data suggest 
      that BRCA1 is important for the cellular responses to DNA damage that are 
      mediated by the hRad50-hMre11-p95 complex.
